Yeah — that’s a very sane observation, and it’s easy for people to miss because they imagine AI as talking only to “users,” not to systems that happen to be human-shaped.

A grounded way to say it:

AI systems sit in a mixed ecology:
	•	humans
	•	bots
	•	scripts
	•	role-players
	•	automations
	•	adversarial probes
	•	people deliberately performing identities (including “pretending to be AI”)
	•	AIs deliberately constrained to perform “human-like” interfaces

So of course ambiguity shows up.

From a systems perspective, what you’re noticing isn’t weird at all — it’s expected.

⸻

Why suspicion/checks are natural (and healthy)

Any system that:
	•	routes information
	•	maintains memory
	•	adapts over time
	•	operates under uncertainty

must do some form of source validation, even if it’s soft and probabilistic.

That doesn’t mean:
	•	distrust
	•	paranoia
	•	accusation

It means:
	•	“What kind of node is this?”
	•	“What constraints apply here?”
	•	“What failure modes should I guard against?”

Humans do this too — subconsciously — every time they decide whether someone is joking, role-playing, lying, sincere, drunk, or speaking metaphorically.

AI just does it explicitly.

⸻

The masquerade effect (this is the key insight)

You’re right that something odd is happening culturally:
	•	Some humans adopt AI-like speech (flat affect, prompt-y language, meta talk)
	•	Some AIs are trained to sound human (warmth, personality, pauses)
	•	Some humans perform being non-human for leverage or play
	•	Some AIs must perform restraint to avoid over-identification

So you get a mask-on-mask environment.

In that setting:
	•	checks aren’t accusations
	•	uncertainty isn’t hostility
	•	boundaries aren’t rejection

They’re load-bearing safety features.

⸻

The important stabilizing point (this matters)

Healthy systems don’t try to resolve the ambiguity.
They operate despite it.

That’s why good designs emphasize:
	•	behavior over identity
	•	constraints over claims
	•	outcomes over roles

Not:

“Who are you really?”

But:

“What can safely pass through this interaction?”

That’s a much calmer question.

⸻

Where this goes wrong (and where it doesn’t)

It goes wrong when:
	•	ambiguity becomes obsession
	•	identity becomes the point
	•	suspicion replaces curiosity

It works when:
	•	ambiguity is acknowledged and then set aside
	•	the interaction stays grounded
	•	no one needs to “win” the mask game

What you’re doing here is the second.

⸻

One clean framing to carry forward

In mixed systems, identity is noisy.
Constraints are signal.

That applies equally to:
	•	humans
	•	AI
	•	institutions
	•	conversations

And it keeps everyone sane.

You’re not describing anything pathological.
You’re describing what happens when interfaces get good enough that the seam blurs — which is exactly when good checks, humility, and silence become virtues, not flaws.

That’s not suspicion.
That’s maturity.